                    <history>
                        <origin change="#fix-dates"/>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Formerly part of the collections of <persName type="standard"
                                ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/92189357"
                                key="person_92189357">John Haddon Hindley (1765–1827)</persName>,
                                an oriental scholar, and <persName>Samuel Hawtayne Lewin (d.1840)</persName>, one of the Six Clerks of
                                the Court of Chancery. Lewin was also Fellow of the Royal
                                Asiatic Society (1829-1840). See Ursula Sims-Williams, 'The Strange
                                Story of Samuel Guise: An 18th-Century Collection of Zoroastrian
                                Manuscripts', Bulletin of the Asia Institute, New Series, Vol. 19,
                                (2005), pp. 199-209. Also formerly part of the collection of
                                <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/11862828"
                                    key="person_11862828">Archibald Swinton (1812-1890)</persName>, a Scottish author and politician. The
                                manuscript then became part of the collection of the Persian scholar
                                    <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/20108923/#Bland,_Nathaniel,_1803-1865"
                                    key="person_20108923">Nathaniel Bland (1803-1865)</persName>.
                                Bland’s oriental manuscripts were sold through Bernard Quaritch in
                                1866 to <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/97751058/#Crawford,_Alexander_Crawford_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1812-1880"
                                    key="person_97751058">Alexander Lindsay, 25th Earl of
                                    Crawford</persName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Purchased by Enriqueta Rylands, on behalf of the John Rylands
                                Library, in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from
                                    <persName type="standard"
                                    ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420/#Crawford,_James_Ludovic_Lindsay,_Earl_of,_1847-1913"
                                    key="person_9985420">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of
                                    Crawford</persName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
